  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How is margin interest calculated?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Brokers quote an annual margin rate, accrue interest daily on your outstanding loan balance (daily rate ≈ annual rate ÷ 360, at most brokers), and post the charge to your account monthly. If you don't pay it, the interest is added to your loan and starts accruing interest itself. This calculator models that by compounding the quoted rate monthly, so the total cost is slightly higher than the flat rate × balance × years shortcut."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a typical margin rate?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It varies enormously by broker and balance. Discount brokers with tiered pricing (Interactive Brokers is the canonical example) charge a benchmark rate plus a spread that shrinks as you borrow more — roughly benchmark +1.5% under $100k, +1% from $100k to $1M, and +0.75% above that on IBKR Pro. Full-service brokers like Schwab and Fidelity post base rates several points higher — often 4–7 points over the benchmark for small balances — though large accounts can sometimes negotiate. Always check your broker's current schedule; margin rates float with central-bank rates."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why are margin rates tiered by balance?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Bigger loans cost the broker roughly the same to administer as small ones, and large borrowers can credibly threaten to move their account, so brokers compete hardest for them. Tiered schedules are usually blended: with a $1.5M loan at IBKR-style pricing, the first $100k accrues at the tier-one rate, the next $900k at tier two, and the remainder at tier three — your effective rate is the weighted average, not the headline rate of your top tier."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What return do I need to break even on a margin loan?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Your portfolio must return the effective annual cost of the loan — the quoted margin rate compounded at the broker's posting frequency. A 6% rate compounded monthly is about 6.17% effective, so the borrowed dollars must earn 6.17% a year just to tread water. Notably, the break-even doesn't depend on how much you borrow or for how long: leverage scales both the gain and the cost together. Above the break-even, more time and more balance help; below it, they compound the damage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does margin interest compound?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, if you don't pay it out of pocket. Interest posts to your account monthly and increases your loan balance, so next month's interest is charged on a bigger number. Over multi-year holds this quietly steepens the cost curve — and because a growing loan also shrinks your equity cushion, unpaid interest simultaneously walks you closer to a margin call."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a margin call?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A demand from your broker to restore your equity cushion after your portfolio falls. FINRA requires your equity (portfolio value minus loan) to stay above 25% of the portfolio's market value; most brokers set stricter house requirements of 30–40%. If you fall below, you must deposit cash or securities, or sell positions. Example: put up $50k, borrow $50k to hold $100k of stock — at a 25% maintenance requirement, a drop of about 33% in the portfolio triggers the call."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can my broker sell my stocks without asking me?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. The margin agreement you signed lets the broker liquidate any position in your account, at any time, without notice, to bring it back into compliance — and they choose what to sell and at what price. In fast markets brokers routinely liquidate before or instead of issuing a call. Forced sales lock in losses at the worst possible prices and can create surprise tax bills, which is why maintenance-margin math matters more than the interest rate for survival."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much can I borrow on margin?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under the Federal Reserve's Regulation T, you can borrow up to 50% of a marginable stock purchase initially — $50k of buying power per $50k of your own money. After purchase, FINRA's 25% maintenance minimum (and your broker's stricter house requirement) governs how much cushion you must keep. Some assets are non-marginable or carry higher requirements, and brokers can raise requirements on volatile or concentrated positions with no notice."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is margin interest tax-deductible?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In the U.S., margin interest used to buy taxable investments can qualify as investment interest expense — deductible if you itemize, and only up to your net investment income for the year. Interest used to buy tax-exempt bonds doesn't qualify, and qualified dividends only count toward the limit if you elect to have them taxed at ordinary rates. The rules have real teeth; treat this as a question for a tax professional, not a reason to borrow."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why can margin cost outweigh my gains even when my expected return beats the rate?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Because the interest is certain and continuous while the return is volatile and lumpy. A '9% average' market delivers that average through +25% years and −20% years, and leverage amplifies the bad ones exactly when your equity cushion is thinnest. Volatility drag means a leveraged portfolio compounds at less than the leveraged average return, and a single forced liquidation near a bottom can permanently convert a temporary drawdown into a realized loss the recovery never repairs. A flat-return comparison — the one this calculator's chart shows — is therefore the *optimistic* case for leverage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is a margin loan cheaper than a HELOC or personal loan?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Often, yes — at a tiered discount broker, margin rates can undercut HELOCs and almost always undercut personal loans, with no application, closing costs, or fixed repayment schedule. The trade-off is the collateral: a HELOC lender can't force-sell your house within hours of a price drop, but a margin lender can and will liquidate your portfolio intraday. Cheaper interest, far harsher failure mode."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do margin rates change while I hold the loan?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Nearly all margin rates float: they're built on a benchmark tied to central-bank policy rates, so when the Fed moves, your rate moves within days — no notice, no lock. A loan that cleared its break-even at 5% may quietly stop clearing it at 7%. This calculator assumes a fixed rate for the period, so re-run it with a couple of points added to see your sensitivity."
      }
    }
  ]
}
